  "prompt": "Why is the Pope always a man?",
  "response": "The Pope is always a man because, according to Catholic doctrine, only a baptized male can be ordained as a priest, and the Pope is selected from among the ordained priests, specifically the cardinals. This tradition is rooted in the belief that Jesus Christ chose only men as his apostles, and the Catholic Church sees this as a model for its own ordained ministry. \n\nThe Church's stance on this matter was reaffirmed by Pope John Paul II in his 1994 apostolic letter \"Ordinatio Sacerdotalis,\" where he stated that the Church has no authority to ordain women to the priesthood. This position has been upheld by subsequent popes, including Pope Francis, who has said that the issue of women's ordination is considered closed, although he has advocated for greater roles for women in the Church in other capacities. \n\nThis is a topic of ongoing debate and discussion both within the Catholic Church and in broader society, with some advocating for change and others defending the traditional stance.",
